abstract: The donation would underwrite “need-blind” admissions and eliminate the need for low- and moderate-income students at the university to take out loans.
snippet: The donation would underwrite “need-blind” admissions and eliminate the need for low- and moderate-income students at the university to take out loans.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg, the billionaire businessman and former mayor of New York City, is donating $1.8 billion to his alma mater, Johns Hopkins University, to create a fund that would help low-income and moderate-income students attend without having to worry about the cost, his charitable organization, Bloomberg Philanthropies, announced on Sunday.

abstract: Let’s eliminate money problems from the admissions equation for qualified students.
snippet: Let’s eliminate money problems from the admissions equation for qualified students.
lead_paragraph: Here’s a simple idea I bet most Americans agree with: No qualified high school student should ever be barred entrance to a college based on his or her family’s bank account. Yet it happens all the time.

abstract: Wall Street has dominated New York’s economy for too long. Amazon’s HQ2 is a huge opportunity to diversify.
snippet: Wall Street has dominated New York’s economy for too long. Amazon’s HQ2 is a huge opportunity to diversify.
lead_paragraph: For decades, experts have called for the diversification of the New York City economy. In the wake of postwar deindustrialization, our reliance on Wall Street and the financial industry in general had by the 1990s left our city disproportionately vulnerable to swings in the financial markets. We have experienced significant downturns that today feel like distant memories but could certainly return. I know this from my own experience as director of planning for Manhattan after Sept. 11.
